english:
  title: Stele Inscription for National Preceptor Jingak of Dangyoksa Temple, the Second Generation Successor at Jogyesan
  author: Lee Gyubo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Since the transmission of mind-dharma began, all monks who sit upright in their practice naturally seek to compete with frost and moonlight in purity. Yet when it comes to the rise and fall of names in the Chan lineage, few can truly release such attachments. Some retreat to mountain valleys, secretly cultivating the essentials of mind, desperately wishing not to be entangled by reputation's burden—yet reputation pursues them nonetheless. Who is such a person? Our National Preceptor Jingak exemplifies this. More remarkably, from his youth he already devoted himself to letters and scholarship. Soon after, he passed the civil service examination—his learning was keen, his fortune bright. Had he merely waited a moment longer, he would have risen through the ranks, becoming a celebrated scholar-official. Instead, he renounced the success within reach, lamenting that he had not earlier cast off worldly entanglement. In this we see his transcendent spirit soaring beyond the world. Comparing him to the ancients, he resembles Dharma Fusion or the Chan Master Tianran.

    The National Preceptor's dharma name was Huixin, styled Yongyi, calling himself the Unclothed One. His secular surname was Choe, personal name Sik, from Hwasun County in Naju. His father, named Wan, was a provincial recommendation scholar. His mother, née Pae, dreamed that heaven's gate opened wide, and dreamed of thunder three times. She then became pregnant, carrying the child for twelve months before birth. The amniotic membrane wrapped around him like a monk's robe. When it broke, his eyes remained closed for seven days before opening. After nursing, he would turn away from his mother and sleep facing outward—his parents marveled. His father died early. He begged his mother to let him become a monk, but she refused, forcing him to study Confucian learning. Yet he constantly recited sutras and mantras, and eventually attained spiritual power. He delighted in destroying shamanic shrines and healing people's ailments. In the sixth year of Seung'an, in the cyclical year sinyu, he passed the civil service examination and entered the National Academy. Upon hearing of his mother's illness, he returned home. While caring for her at his uncle Pae Gwangh-an's house, he entered the Samadhi of Buddha-contemplation. His mother dreamed of buddhas and bodhisattvas appearing throughout the four directions; upon waking, she recovered. His uncle and aunt dreamed the same dream. The following year his mother passed away.

    At that time, National Preceptor BoZhao had newly established the Suseon Society at Jogyesan, where his teaching flourished greatly. The Master went immediately to pay his respects, arranged an offering meal for his mother, and requested tonsure. The preceptor granted it. That night his uncle dreamed of the Master's deceased mother ascending to heaven. When the Master first visited the National Preceptor, the preceptor saw him as a monk. Upon seeing him again, he realized otherwise. Previously, the National Preceptor had dreamed of Chan Master Xuedou Xiangjue entering the monastery, which seemed remarkable. The next day the Master came to pay respects. This strengthened the preceptor's regard.

    The Master once lived on Wushan, sitting on a stone slab, cultivating meditation day and night. At the fifth watch he would sing gathas loudly, his voice carrying ten li distant, never missing a moment. People used this to mark the dawn. He also lived on Jirisan at Golden Platform Hermitage, sitting in meditation while snow piled above his head, remaining motionless like deadwood. The assembly thought him dead and shook him, but he did not respond. Such was his austere practice—only one whose spirit merged with the Way, transcending life and death, abandoning the body, could achieve this.

    In the autumn of yichou, when National Preceptor Bozhao was at Yibaoshan, the Master and several monks set out to visit. Resting at the mountain's base, a thousand paces from the hermitage, they heard the preceptor's voice calling an attendant from within. The Master composed a gatha:

    "Calling to the boy pierces misty pine and vine,
    Tea's fragrance drifts on stone-path wind."

    Upon meeting the preceptor, he presented this verse. The preceptor confirmed it and gave the Master a fan from his hand. The Master responded:

    "Yesterday within your hand,
    Today rests in your disciple's palm.
    Should burning haste race wild,
    I'll fan the clear wind forth."

    The preceptor increasingly recognized his depth. Once while accompanying the preceptor, he pointed to a broken shoe and asked, "The shoe is here—where is the person?" The Master replied, "Why didn't we see each other then?" The preceptor was greatly pleased. Later, when Zhaozhou's "the dog has no Buddha-nature" was raised, and Dahui's ten types of ailments were asked, no one answered. The Master said, "Only those with three types of ailments understand this meaning." The preceptor asked, "Where do those three types breathe out?" The Master struck the window once. The preceptor laughed heartily. Returning to his quarters, he called the Master in private, saying with joy, "Having obtained you, I die without regret. You must assume the burden of Buddha-dharma and not forsake my original vow."

    In the wuchen year of Taihe, the preceptor wanted the Master to succeed him. He immediately retired to Anguifeng. The Master respectfully declined and departed for Jirisan, severing his traces for several years. In the gengwu year of Da'an, the National Preceptor entered parinirvana. His disciples reported to the throne and received an imperial decree to have the Master continue his lineage. The Master reluctantly entered the monastery and opened the dharma hall. Thereupon scholars and practitioners from all directions, together with esteemed lay people and hidden sages, gathered like clouds and shadows—none failed to come. The hall became too narrow. The king heard of this and ordered his officials to expand it, repeatedly sending imperial messengers to oversee the work. Thus it was enlarged, and the emperor sent embroidered robes, monk's garments, tea, incense, precious vessels, and requested the dharma essentials. The Master composed the Heart Essence, which was transmitted and remains in the world today.

    From this time, ministers, nobles, and regional lords, hearing of his virtue, either paid distant respects as disciples or came personally. The lineages of Chan that boasted of their strength, claiming none their equal, would upon seeing the Master once become startled, change their countenance, and vie to serve him. The Court Official Choe of Jinyang, hearing of the Master's renown, yearned to invite him to the capital, but the Master never went. Yet across a thousand li their minds connected as if face to face. He sent two sons to attend the Master, providing all necessities without fail—tea, incense, medicines, delicacies, treasures, and robes, the provisions never ceasing day or night.

    When the present emperor ascended the throne, he granted the Master the title Seonsa, then advanced him to Dae Seonsa. Without passing through the selection examination, the Master directly entered the monastic hierarchy—the first to do so. The Chancellor Choe Hongyun had once presided over the civil service examination when the Master came from his school. Soon after Choe rose to prime minister while the Master resided at Jogyesan. The chancellor called himself a disciple and wished to register in the Society, sending a letter stating, "Buddha's Light delighted in accompanying the scholar Bai, personally transmitting the Great Vehicle. Songshan welcomed the secretary He, secretly conveying the wondrous meaning." The Master replied, "I was once in your school; you now enter my society. We exchange roles of guest and host, teacher and disciple." People spread this as a remarkable exchange.

    In the giyou year of Zhenyou, the emperor ordered the Master to reside at Dangyoksa Temple. Though the Master repeatedly declined, permission was not granted. The following year he entered the monastery, though he kept Jogyesan as his primary residence. In the middle winter of guisi, falling ill at Jogyesan, the Official of Jinyang heard and was greatly alarmed. He reported to the throne, which sent an imperial physician. In spring the Master moved to Yuedensi. When Makgu entered his room, the Master said, "This old one is in great pain today." Makgu asked, "Why is it so?" The Master responded in verse:

    "Where all sufferings cannot reach,
    There lies another heaven and earth.
    If you ask what place this is,
    It is the gate of great nirvana."

    Raising his fist, the Master said, "This fist can explain Chan. Do you believe it?" He then opened his palm: "Five fingers spread unevenly. Clenched, they become one mass. Opening and closing freely, one and many have no obstruction. Yet this is not the fundamental teaching of the fist. What is the fundamental teaching?" He struck the window once and laughed heartily.

    On the twenty-sixth day of the sixth month in the jiawu year, the Master summoned his disciples to entrust matters. He said to Makgu, "This old one is very busy today." Makgu asked, "What is it?" The Master replied, "This old one is very busy today." Makgu stood speechless. The Master smiled, sat in full lotus, and passed away. The next day he was cremated at the north peak of Yuedensi. His relics were brought back to the home monastery. The emperor, hearing this, was deeply grieved and posthumously granted him the title National Preceptor Jingak. In the middle summer of yiwei, he was buried at the north side of Guangyuansi, and a stupa was erected. The emperor named it the Stupa of Perfect Illumination. The Master lived fifty-seven years and kept the monastic precepts for thirty-two.

    From the time of the Master's illness, the mountain where he dwelt experienced landslides, and flocks of birds filled the valley, crying for more than ten days—how wondrous! His lifetime of subtle resonance with the miraculous is recorded by his disciples: a turtle receiving precepts, a toad listening to dharma, crows shuffling divination sticks, an ox kneeling on the path. Such are world-renowned accounts, yet unsuitable for scholarly record, so I do not elaborate here.

    The Master possessed an equanimous and substantial nature. Having mastered texts both Buddhist and Confucian, when expounding Buddha-dharma or composing verses, he moved with the ease of a master butcher's blade. How else could one who never set foot in the capital come to be so universally revered? Truly, one may call him the correct eye of the Chan lineage, a living bodhisattva in flesh.

    The Dharma heir, the venerable Mongru, is also a Dharma King. He requested the layman Jeongbun to compile the Master's biography and petition for this stele. The official said, "The Master greatly benefited people during his life; a stele must be erected." He reported to the throne, which commanded this humble servant to inscribe it:

    After the smile of transmission,
    Who carries the dharma forward?
    In our three Han kingdoms,
    National Preceptor Jingak received it.
    Born swaddled in priestly robes—
    An omen already wondrous.
    Achieving the correct eye,
    He transcended his age.
    Self-realized Buddha-nature,
    Sharing it through words.
    Without transmitted dharma,
    What would the lost ones grasp?
    Ascending the teaching seat,
    His words flowed like spring streams.
    The Master's tongue is Buddha's mind,
    Buddha's mind is the Master's tongue.
    Silence itself is natural ease,
    Yet speech too brings delight.
    His body hidden in deep rock,
    How did his name escape?
    Learners gathered in clouds,
    His assembly thick as mist.
    Questions came from every side—
    No moment for response.
    He gave us rest,
    Some hours of peaceful sitting.
    Scattered by prajna's scent,
    Myriad lords sought admission,
    Kings and princes bowed from afar,
    As if receiving his teachings direct.
    Thirty-two years as monk,
    His abundant grace touched many,
    Leaving their hearts
    Fully satisfied.
    The dharma pillar crumbled—
    Tears flowed from all eyes.
    The emperor grieved deeply,
    His face darkened with sorrow.
    Honoring his passing,
    Imperial kindness unbounded,
    He ordered this servant
    To carve this great monument.
    May this mountain crumble,
    This stone never move.
  footnotes:
    - 'National Preceptor Bozhao (普照國師): An influential Chan master of Goryeo who established the Suseon Society at Jogyesan, representing the Jogye school of Korean Buddhism.'
    - 'Jogyesan (曹溪山): A sacred Buddhist mountain in Korea, site of major Chan/Seon temples, echoing Caoxi Mountain in China, the home of the Sixth Patriarch Huineng.'
    - 'Chan Master Xuedou Xiangjue (雪竇顯禪師): A renowned Song-era Chinese Chan master whose teaching style influenced Korean Seon.'
    - 'Zhaozhou''s ''the dog has no Buddha-nature'': A famous Chan gongan (公案/koan) from Zhaozhou Congshen that tests the practitioner''s understanding of Buddha-nature.'
    - 'Dahui (大慧杲): An influential Song-era Chan master known for his systematic teaching methods, particularly the hwadu (話頭) practice.'
    - 'The five-finger imagery: A classic Chan teaching device representing the relationship between multiplicity and unity, used to test understanding of non-duality.'
    - 'Cremation at Yuedensi: Following Chan Buddhist practice, the Master''s remains were cremated, with relics collected to create a stupa (stone pagoda) as a memorial and object of veneration.'
